9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to S.P. 524, L.D. 1294, “An Act to Expand the
10 Dependent Exemption Tax Credit”
11 Amend the bill by striking out everything after the enacting clause and inserting the
12 following:
13 'Sec. 1. 36 MRSA §5219-SS, sub-§4, as amended by PL 2023, c. 412, Pt. ZZZ, §6,
14 is further amended to read:
15 4. Refundability; phase-out. For tax years beginning before January 1, 2024, the
16 credit allowed by this section may not reduce the tax otherwise due under this Part to less
17 than zero. For tax years beginning on or after January 1, 2024, the credit allowed under
18 subsections 1, 1‑A, 3 and 3‑A, as increased by subsection 5 for tax years beginning on or
19 after January 1, 2025, is refundable. The amount of the credit allowed by this section must
20 be reduced, but not below zero, by $7.50 for each $1,000 or fraction thereof by which the
21 taxpayer's Maine adjusted gross income exceeds $400,000 in the case of a joint return and
22 $200,000 in any other case.
23 For tax years beginning before January 1, 2025, the amount of the credit allowed by this
24 section must be reduced, but not below zero, by $7.50 for each $1,000 or fraction thereof
25 by which the taxpayer's Maine adjusted gross income exceeds $400,000 in the case of a
26 joint return and $200,000 in any other case.
27 For tax years beginning on or after January 1, 2025, the amount of the credit allowed by
28 this section, as increased by subsection 5, must be reduced, but not below zero, by $20 for
29 each $500 or fraction thereof by which the taxpayer's Maine adjusted gross income
30 exceeds:
31 A. For a single individual, $125,000;
32 B. For an individual filing as a head of household, $150,000;
33 C. For individuals filing married joint returns or surviving spouses, $175,000; and
34 D. For a married individual filing a separate return, 1/2 of the applicable amount under
35 paragraph C.
